  "prompt": "Will the new Rs 2000 notes carry a nano GPS chip? Will it really Help?",
  "response": "The claim that new Rs 2000 notes will carry a nano GPS chip has been widely debunked. When the Rs 2000 note was introduced by the Reserve Bank of India (RBI) in 2016, rumors circulated about the presence of a nano GPS chip embedded in the notes for tracking purposes. However, these claims were false. There is no technology or chip in these notes that would allow tracking of their location.\n\nIncluding a GPS chip in currency notes poses significant practical and technical challenges. A GPS chip requires a power source to function, which is not feasible in the thin dimensions of a paper note. Additionally, such technology would significantly increase the cost of producing the currency and would raise privacy and surveillance concerns.\n\nIn summary, there is no nano GPS chip in Rs 2000 notes, and the rumor was a myth. Implementing such a feature would currently be impractical and unnecessary for tracking purposes.",
